<script>
const topics = [
{num:"Topic 1",title:"Terror & coercion in consolidating the Soviet state (1917–1924)",question:"Evaluate the role of coercion and terror in the consolidation of the Soviet state between 1917 and 1924.",thesis:"Terror was essential but insufficient alone — the Bolsheviks consolidated power through a combination of organised violence, the elimination of political alternatives, and pragmatic popular policies like the NEP.",columns:[{title:"Evidence of coercion",color:"for",points:[{text:"Constituent Assembly dissolved (Jan 1918)",sub:"Bolsheviks lost election — closed it by force"},{text:"Ex-tsarist officers forced into Red Army",sub:"Families held hostage as guarantee"},{text:"Censorship of press from 1917"},{text:"One-party state established by 1921–22",sub:"Mensheviks and SRs banned"}]},{title:"Evidence of terror",color:"against",points:[{text:"Cheka founded Dec 1917 — secret police",sub:"28,000+ executions/year (Ryan, 2012)"},{text:"Red Terror declared Sept 1918 after SR assassination attempt on Lenin"},{text:"Romanovs executed July 1918",sub:"Eliminated monarchist rallying point"},{text:"Kronstadt Mutiny crushed 1921",sub:"Trotsky — even former supporters shot"}]}],other:{title:"Other factors (balance your essay with these)",points:[{text:"Civil War victory (1918–21) eliminated the realistic White alternative"},{text:"NEP (1921) — pragmatic retreat; won back peasant support"},{text:"Bolshevik ideology gave the regime a unifying mission"},{text:"Trotsky's military genius in building the Red Army"}]},tip:"IB rewards balance — don't say 'only terror'. Argue terror was necessary to survive the Civil War but the NEP showed Lenin understood you also need consent. Best conclusion: terror removed opposition; popular policies built stability."},
{num:"Topic 2",title:"Collapse of the Provisional Government (1917)",question:"Discuss the view that the Provisional Government collapsed because of the power of the Soviets.",thesis:"The Soviets weakened the Provisional Government through Dual Power, but the real cause of its collapse was its own failures — continuing the war, ignoring land reform, and losing army support — which the Bolsheviks then exploited.",columns:[{title:"Role of the Soviets",color:"for",points:[{text:"Dual Power — Soviet Order No. 1 gave soviets control of army",sub:"Officers had to be confirmed by soldiers' committees"},{text:"Petrograd Soviet refused to endorse war continuation"},{text:"Bolsheviks won majority on Petrograd & Moscow Soviets by Sept 1917"},{text:"Red Guards (Soviet militia) crushed Kornilov — PG depended on them"}]},{title:"PG's own failures",color:"against",points:[{text:"No democratic legitimacy — self-appointed from Duma"},{text:"Continued the war — massive unpopularity (June Offensive failed)"},{text:"Land question ignored — peasants seized land anyway"},{text:"Kornilov Affair — Kerensky armed the Bolsheviks, then couldn't disarm them"}]}],other:{title:"Key events to reference",points:[{text:"Lenin's April Theses — 'All power to the Soviets', Peace Land Bread"},{text:"July Days — premature uprising, Lenin fled to Finland"},{text:"October 24–25 — MRC seized telegraph, bridges, Winter Palace"},{text:"PG had almost no defenders — only cadets and Women's Battalion"}]},tip:"The question asks you to DISCUSS the Soviet power argument — so engage with it directly, but then show it's only part of the answer. The Soviets created weakness; the PG's own decisions made collapse inevitable."},
{num:"Topic 3",title:"WWI as the main cause of the February Revolution",question:"Russia's participation in the First World War was the main cause of the February/March 1917 Revolution. To what extent do you agree?",thesis:"WWI was the immediate trigger of the February Revolution, but it acted as a catalyst for long-term systemic failures of tsarism — without those underlying weaknesses, the war alone could not have caused revolution.",columns:[{title:"Long-term causes (pre-war)",color:"lt",points:[{text:"Autocratic tsarism — no real parliament, repression of opposition"},{text:"1905 Revolution — October Manifesto failed to deliver real reform"},{text:"Duma weakness — Nicholas II undermined it repeatedly"},{text:"Peasant poverty, land hunger, rapid industrialisation with poor conditions"},{text:"Growth of revolutionary parties — SRs, Mensheviks, Bolsheviks"},{text:"Stolypin's reforms incomplete; Lena Goldfields massacre 1912"}]},{title:"Short-term causes (war-related)",color:"st",points:[{text:"Military disasters — Tannenberg 1914, Masurian Lakes 1914"},{text:"1.8 million dead by 1917; 5 million POWs"},{text:"Nicholas took personal command of army 1915 — blamed for defeats"},{text:"Rasputin's influence — undermined confidence in monarchy"},{text:"Bread shortages in Petrograd — women's bread riots 8 March 1917"},{text:"Petrograd garrison mutinied — refused to fire on protesters"}]}],other:{title:"February events (the spark)",points:[{text:"International Women's Day 8 March — bread riots in Petrograd"},{text:"Putilov factory workers strike — 200,000 on streets"},{text:"Tsar ordered troops to fire — Volynsky regiment refused and joined protesters"},{text:"Nicholas abdicated 2 March 1917 — no support from generals"}]},tip:"The best IB answer argues war was the main SHORT-TERM cause but the system was already broken. Use the phrase 'catalyst' — the war ignited powder already laid by tsarism's failures."},
{num:"Topic 4",title:"Lenin's foreign policy — ideology vs pragmatism",question:"Lenin's foreign relations were motivated by practical concerns and not ideology. Discuss.",thesis:"Lenin's foreign policy was primarily driven by pragmatic necessity — the weakness of Soviet Russia forced compromise — but ideological commitment to world revolution was a constant undercurrent that surfaced when circumstances allowed.",columns:[{title:"Pragmatic decisions",color:"for",points:[{text:"Treaty of Brest-Litovsk 1918 — lost huge territory to end the war",sub:"Lenin overruled Trotsky; survival first"},{text:"Treaty of Riga 1921 — ended Russo-Polish War, accepted losses"},{text:"Recognised independence of Finland, Baltic States"},{text:"Treaty of Rapallo 1922 — trade deal with Germany, mutual benefit"},{text:"Trade agreements with Britain 1921 — economic pragmatism"}]},{title:"Ideological decisions",color:"against",points:[{text:"Comintern (Third International) 1919 — spread world revolution",sub:"Direct ideological tool"},{text:"Russo-Polish War 1920 — Lenin pushed west hoping to spark German revolution"},{text:"Support for communist parties in Germany, Hungary, etc."},{text:"Long-term goal of world revolution never abandoned"}]}],other:{title:"Context to explain pragmatism",points:[{text:"Allied intervention in Civil War — surrounded by hostile powers"},{text:"Soviet Russia economically devastated — needed trade and recognition"},{text:"World revolution failed to materialise (Germany 1918–19, Hungary 1919)"},{text:"NEP showed Lenin's domestic pragmatism mirrored his foreign policy realism"}]},tip:"Best argument: Lenin was a pragmatist in the short term because he had to be — but he never gave up on ideology as a long-term goal. The Comintern proves ideological commitment even while signing capitalist trade deals."},
{num:"Topic 5",title:"Compare causes of February and October Revolutions",question:"Compare and contrast the causes of the February/March and October/November Revolutions in 1917.",thesis:"Both revolutions were caused by the failures of the ruling government and the impact of WWI, but they differed fundamentally in nature — February was a spontaneous popular uprising, October was a carefully planned Bolshevik coup.",columns:[{title:"Similarities",color:"for",points:[{text:"Both driven by WWI — military failures, economic collapse, food shortages"},{text:"Both against a government seen as illegitimate and incompetent"},{text:"Both involved the military withdrawing support from the government"},{text:"Economic crisis and food shortages in both cases"},{text:"Soviet and worker organisations played a role in both"}]},{title:"Differences",color:"against",points:[{text:"February — spontaneous mass uprising; October — planned coup d'état"},{text:"February against the Tsar; October against the Provisional Government"},{text:"February had massive popular participation; October had very little"},{text:"February: unplanned, no single leader; October: Lenin and Trotsky directed it"},{text:"February bloodier; October almost bloodless (5 soldiers, 1 sailor killed)"}]}],other:{title:"Specific events to use as evidence",points:[{text:"February: Women's Day bread riots, Putilov strike, garrison mutiny"},{text:"October: MRC seized key points in Petrograd overnight"},{text:"Kornilov Affair Aug 1917 — weakened PG, armed Bolsheviks"},{text:"Bolsheviks had majority in Petrograd & Moscow soviets by Sept 1917"}]},tip:"IB specifically states: 'both similarities and differences must be clearly indicated but there does not need to be an equal number of both.' Structure: intro with overall argument → 2–3 similarities → 2–3 differences → conclusion on which was more significant."},
{num:"Topic 6",title:"Lenin's career — 'one step forward, two steps back'",question:"To what extent can 'one step forward, two steps back' be applied to Lenin's revolutionary career and rule of the USSR 1918–1924?",thesis:"The quotation captures Lenin's career well — repeated setbacks followed by advances — but ultimately the 'steps forward' were permanent (Bolshevik power, Civil War victory) while the 'steps back' were tactical retreats he controlled.",columns:[{title:"Steps back (setbacks)",color:"against",points:[{text:"Multiple exiles — Siberia, then Western Europe"},{text:"1905 Revolution failed — hopes raised, crushed"},{text:"Had to flee after July Days 1917 (disguised)"},{text:"Lost Constituent Assembly election Jan 1918"},{text:"Brest-Litovsk — humiliating territorial losses"},{text:"War Communism failed — famine 1921, Kronstadt revolt"},{text:"Strokes 1922, 1923 — incapacitated, could not choose successor"}]},{title:"Steps forward (advances)",color:"for",points:[{text:"Return to Russia April 1917 (German sealed train)"},{text:"October Revolution — seized power"},{text:"Dissolved Constituent Assembly — asserted Bolshevik control"},{text:"Won Civil War 1921"},{text:"NEP 1921 — pragmatic recovery, stabilised economy"},{text:"One-party state fully established by 1922"}]}],other:{title:"Wider evaluation",points:[{text:"The 'steps back' were often Lenin's own choices — Brest-Litovsk, NEP — tactical retreats"},{text:"Greatest 'step back' was his illness — lost control over succession struggle"},{text:"Testament (1923) — warned against Stalin but was too ill to act"},{text:"He never fully recovered the 'step forward' of political health"}]},tip:"This is a Higher Level question. Use the quotation as a genuine analytical framework, not just decoration. Show you understand Lenin chose some retreats consciously — that's what makes him a great politician, not a failure."},
{num:"Topic 7",title:"Was Lenin a ruthless dictator?",question:"The Bolshevik state under Lenin between 1918 and 1924 was a ruthless dictatorship, caring little for the Russian people. To what extent do you agree?",thesis:"Lenin's state was undeniably authoritarian and often brutal, but to call it entirely uncaring oversimplifies — the NEP showed pragmatic concern for stability, and Lenin's ideology genuinely (if distortedly) claimed to serve the working class.",columns:[{title:"Evidence it WAS a dictatorship",color:"against",points:[{text:"Cheka — secret police with power of summary execution"},{text:"Red Terror — mass executions, hostage-taking"},{text:"Religion suppressed — church property seized"},{text:"Civil service and professionals persecuted as 'class enemies'"},{text:"One-party state — opposition parties banned by 1921"},{text:"Censorship and propaganda apparatus"},{text:"Famine during War Communism — grain requisitioning caused starvation"}]},{title:"Qualifications / counter-arguments",color:"for",points:[{text:"NEP 1921 — reversed War Communism to relieve peasant suffering"},{text:"Decree on Land 1917 — gave peasants what they wanted"},{text:"Decree on Peace — ended the war, hugely popular"},{text:"Social reforms — women's equality, education expansion"},{text:"Terror was partly a response to assassination attempts and Civil War emergency"}]}],other:{title:"Comparative scale of repression",points:[{text:"28,000+ executions/year under Lenin vs 270/year under Tsarism (Ryan, 2012)"},{text:"But Stalin later far exceeded this — Lenin's dictatorship was not the worst"},{text:"'Former people' — aristocracy, clergy, officers — systematically persecuted"}]},tip:"Agree substantially but with nuance. 'Ruthless' yes; 'caring little for the people' needs challenging — his ideology was genuinely about the workers, even if his methods were brutal. High-band answers use Ryan's statistics."},
{num:"Topic 8",title:"Lenin's success in solving the problems he faced",question:"How successful was Lenin (1917–1924) in solving the problems he faced?",thesis:"Lenin was broadly successful in securing Bolshevik power and ending the war, but mixed in his economic solutions — War Communism caused catastrophic famine, requiring the ideological compromise of the NEP.",columns:[{title:"Problems faced",color:"against",points:[{text:"WWI still ongoing — army collapsing, soldiers deserting"},{text:"Civil War 1918–21 — Whites, Allied intervention, Green armies"},{text:"Economic devastation — industry and agriculture collapsed"},{text:"Agrarian crisis — peasant unrest, land hunger"},{text:"Foreign hostility — no diplomatic recognition"},{text:"Rival political parties and opposition movements"}]},{title:"How successful?",color:"for",points:[{text:"Brest-Litovsk 1918 — ended war (at huge cost); survival first",sub:"SUCCESS"},{text:"Civil War victory 1921 — Trotsky's Red Army defeated Whites",sub:"SUCCESS"},{text:"War Communism — kept army fed but caused famine 1921",sub:"PARTIAL FAILURE"},{text:"NEP 1921 — stabilised economy, won back peasants",sub:"SUCCESS"},{text:"One-party state — eliminated political opposition",sub:"SUCCESS (for regime)"},{text:"Rapallo 1922 — broke diplomatic isolation with Germany",sub:"SUCCESS"}]}],other:{title:"New problems created",points:[{text:"NEP created 'NEPmen' — new capitalist class, ideological contradiction"},{text:"Strokes 1922–23 — failed to solve succession crisis"},{text:"Testament warned against Stalin — but Lenin died before acting on it"},{text:"Terror created fear and resentment; long-term political culture of violence"}]},tip:"Structure around each problem in turn. Evaluate: fully solved? partially? new problems created? The NEP is your best example of solving one problem (famine) while creating another (ideological compromise)."},
{num:"Topic 9",title:"Long-term and short-term causes of the February Revolution",question:"Analyse the long-term and short-term causes of the 1917 February/March Russian Revolution.",thesis:"The February Revolution resulted from the accumulated failures of tsarist rule over decades — political rigidity, social inequality, and economic backwardness — triggered and accelerated by the catastrophic impact of WWI.",columns:[{title:"Long-term causes",color:"lt",points:[{text:"Nature of tsarism — autocratic, repressive, no real parliament"},{text:"Peasant poverty — 80% of population, land hunger, periodic famines"},{text:"Rapid industrialisation — overcrowded cities, terrible working conditions"},{text:"1905 Revolution — failed; October Manifesto not genuinely implemented"},{text:"Weakness of Dumas — Nicholas II dissolved/ignored them"},{text:"Growth of revolutionary parties — SRs, Mensheviks, Bolsheviks, Constitutional Democrats"},{text:"Stolypin's land reforms (1906–11) — incomplete; Stolypin assassinated 1911"}]},{title:"Short-term causes",color:"st",points:[{text:"WWI military disasters — Tannenberg, Masurian Lakes; 1.8m dead"},{text:"Nicholas took personal command of army 1915 — blamed for all defeats"},{text:"Rasputin scandal — Alexandra's influence, undermined royal credibility"},{text:"Bread shortages in Petrograd winter 1916–17"},{text:"Industrial strikes — Putilov workers dismissed Jan 1917"},{text:"International Women's Day — bread riots 8 March 1917"},{text:"Petrograd garrison refused to fire — mutinied and joined protesters"}]}],other:{title:"Final trigger events (Feb–Mar 1917)",points:[{text:"200,000 workers on streets of Petrograd by 10 March"},{text:"Nicholas ordered troops to fire — they refused"},{text:"Duma defied tsar's order to dissolve — formed Provisional Committee"},{text:"Generals advised abdication — Nicholas abdicated 2 March 1917"}]},tip:"IB wants you to clearly label causes as long-term or short-term, but acknowledges the boundary is debatable. The best answers show the LINK between them: long-term problems made Russia unstable; the war made an already unstable system collapse."},
{num:"Topic 10",title:"Impact of WWI on Russia (1914–1924)",question:"Analyse the impact of the First World War on Russia between 1914 and 1924.",thesis:"WWI had a devastating and transformative impact on Russia across the entire period — directly causing two revolutions, enabling the Bolshevik seizure of power, shaping the Civil War, and leaving a legacy of economic ruin that forced even Lenin into ideological compromise.",columns:[{title:"Impact 1914–1917",color:"lt",points:[{text:"Initial patriotism — briefly united country behind Tsar"},{text:"Military failures exposed tsarist incompetence (Tannenberg, Masurian Lakes)"},{text:"Peasant soldiers = agricultural labour lost → food shortages"},{text:"Nicholas took personal command 1915 — personally blamed for disasters"},{text:"Economy strained — inflation, supply shortages"},{text:"Led directly to February Revolution and abdication"}]},{title:"Impact 1917–1924",color:"st",points:[{text:"PG's decision to continue war → its own downfall (October Revolution)"},{text:"Germany sent Lenin in sealed train — deliberately destabilised Russia"},{text:"Brest-Litovsk 1918 — Russia lost 1/3 of European territory"},{text:"Allied intervention in Civil War — Britain, France, USA, Japan backed Whites"},{text:"Allied intervention partly caused by desire to re-open Eastern Front"},{text:"War created culture of violence — used in Civil War, Red Terror"}]}],other:{title:"Long-term legacy",points:[{text:"Economic destruction — famine 1921, industry at 20% of 1913 levels"},{text:"NEP (1921) directly caused by economic devastation from years of war"},{text:"Demographic catastrophe — millions dead from war, civil war, famine, disease"},{text:"War normalised political violence — shaped Bolshevik governing style"}]},tip:"Structure chronologically — 1914–17 (tsarist period), 1917–18 (revolution and Brest-Litovsk), 1918–21 (civil war and Allied intervention), 1921–24 (aftermath). Show the war's impact didn't end in 1918 — it shaped everything up to 1924."},
{num:"Topic 11",title:"Why the Bolsheviks won the Civil War",question:"The political and military weaknesses of the Whites led to Bolshevik victory in the Russian Civil War. Discuss.",thesis:"White weaknesses were significant — divided command, no unifying ideology, limited popular support — but Bolshevik strengths were equally decisive: Trotsky's military organisation, central territory, and effective political leadership.",columns:[{title:"White weaknesses",color:"against",points:[{text:"Divided military command — Yudenich (NW), Denikin (S), Kolchak (E) — never coordinated"},{text:"No unifying ideology — monarchists vs republicans vs SRs"},{text:"No consistent political leadership — Siberia had 19 governments in 1918"},{text:"Peasants feared loss of land if Whites won — limited popular support"},{text:"White armies 'lived off the land' — alienated peasantry with looting"},{text:"Foreign intervention actually hurt Whites politically — looked like traitors"}]},{title:"Bolshevik strengths",color:"for",points:[{text:"Trotsky — brilliant military organiser; built Red Army to 5 million by 1921"},{text:"Used ex-tsarist officers (with families as hostages)"},{text:"Controlled heartland — Moscow, Petrograd, rail network"},{text:"War Communism — ruthless grain requisitioning kept army fed"},{text:"Clear political leadership from Lenin throughout"},{text:"Posed as defenders of Russia against foreign invaders — patriotic appeal"},{text:"Promised peasants they could keep their land"}]}],other:{title:"Key events",points:[{text:"Kronstadt sailors briefly mutinied 1921 — even Red supporters protested War Communism"},{text:"Czech Legion 1918 — complicated the conflict; eventually irrelevant"},{text:"Denikin reached within 250 miles of Moscow 1919 before being pushed back"},{text:"Last White forces evacuated from Crimea Nov 1920"}]},tip:"The question frames it as White weakness — so engage with that first. Then argue Bolshevik strengths were equally important. The best essays show HOW the weaknesses and strengths interacted: e.g. foreign support weakened Whites politically while Trotsky exploited their disunity."},
{num:"Topic 12",title:"Roles of Lenin and Trotsky compared",question:"Compare and contrast the roles of Lenin and Trotsky in the 1917 Bolshevik Revolution and the foundation of the Soviet state until 1924.",thesis:"Lenin and Trotsky were both indispensable — Lenin as the political visionary and strategist who drove the coup forward, Trotsky as the operational genius who organised it and then built the army that secured it.",columns:[{title:"Similarities",color:"for",points:[{text:"Both committed to revolution and agreed on its timing in October"},{text:"Both wanted to end Russian participation in WWI"},{text:"Both supported dissolving the Constituent Assembly"},{text:"Both contributed to Civil War victory"},{text:"Both were intellectuals — writers, orators, ideologues"},{text:"Both took risks for the coup despite Marxist theory not fitting Russia"}]},{title:"Differences",color:"against",points:[{text:"Lenin — political strategist; persuaded Central Committee to act in October"},{text:"Trotsky — operational planner; chaired MRC, organised Red Guard, seized Petrograd"},{text:"Lenin directed from background; Trotsky was the face of the coup"},{text:"Lenin ordered Trotsky to accept Brest-Litovsk terms Trotsky opposed; Trotsky resigned"},{text:"Trotsky built and commanded Red Army — Lenin did not fight"},{text:"Trotsky crushed Kronstadt; Lenin introduced NEP (Trotsky opposed NEP)"}]}],other:{title:"Later significance",points:[{text:"Lenin probably favoured Trotsky as successor — mentioned in Testament"},{text:"Lenin's illness from 1922 left a power vacuum that damaged Trotsky"},{text:"Trotsky was a late convert to Bolshevism (joined 1917) — used against him later"},{text:"After Lenin died 1924 — Stalin outmanoeuvred Trotsky using party apparatus"}]},tip:"The compare/contrast structure: write 2–3 genuine similarity paragraphs, then 2–3 contrast paragraphs. Don't just list — for each point, explain WHY the similarity or difference mattered for the outcome."},
{num:"Topic 13",title:"Lenin combined popular policies and repression",question:"Lenin was able to consolidate Bolshevik rule in Russia by combining popular policies and repression. To what extent do you agree with this statement about Bolshevik rule up to 1924?",thesis:"The combination of popular policies and repression was Lenin's governing formula — neither alone would have sufficed. The popular measures built a base of support while terror neutralised opposition that support could not win over.",columns:[{title:"Popular policies",color:"for",points:[{text:"Decree on Peace — ended the war; enormously popular"},{text:"Decree on Land — peasants could keep seized land (Oct 1917)"},{text:"NEP 1921 — ended War Communism, restored private trade, saved economy"},{text:"Currency reform — stabilised ruble under NEP"},{text:"Social policies — women's equality, secular education"},{text:"Workers' control decrees — appealed to urban proletariat"}]},{title:"Repression",color:"against",points:[{text:"Cheka 1917 — secret police, summary executions"},{text:"Red Terror 1918 — mass executions after SR assassination attempt"},{text:"Constituent Assembly closed by force Jan 1918"},{text:"Kronstadt Mutiny crushed 1921 — even Bolshevik supporters shot"},{text:"Mensheviks and SRs banned — one-party state by 1921–22"},{text:"Censorship of all non-Bolshevik press"}]}],other:{title:"Third factor: elimination of alternatives",points:[{text:"Romanovs executed 1918 — removed monarchist focal point"},{text:"Civil War victory 1921 — no viable military alternative to Bolsheviks"},{text:"By 1922 there was simply no alternative to accept — reinforced consolidation"}]},tip:"This question gives you a clear structure in the statement itself. Agree substantially — but add a third factor (elimination of alternatives) to push into the highest band. Argue the combination worked precisely because each element addressed different opponents."},
{num:"Topic 14",title:"Why the Provisional Government failed to hold power",question:"Why was the Provisional Government in Russia unable to consolidate and maintain its power in 1917?",thesis:"The Provisional Government was fatally weakened by its lack of legitimacy, the structural problem of Dual Power, and its catastrophic decision to continue the war — leaving it vulnerable to the organised Bolshevik coup in October.",columns:[{title:"Structural/political failures",color:"against",points:[{text:"No democratic mandate — self-appointed from Duma; not elected"},{text:"Dual Power — Soviet Order No. 1 gave soldiers' committees authority over military"},{text:"Waiting for Constituent Assembly — delayed all decisive action"},{text:"Coalition governments were weak and constantly reshuffled"},{text:"Kerensky — ineffective, indecisive; the 'persuader-in-chief'"}]},{title:"Policy failures",color:"st",points:[{text:"Continued WWI — June Offensive 1917 was a disaster"},{text:"Failed to address land question — peasants seized land anyway"},{text:"Failed to address food shortages in cities"},{text:"Kornilov Affair Aug 1917 — armed Bolsheviks to defend Petrograd, then couldn't disarm them"},{text:"Lost army loyalty — officers and men both alienated"}]}],other:{title:"Bolshevik strengths as counterpoint",points:[{text:"Lenin's April Theses — clear programme: Peace, Land, Bread, Soviet power"},{text:"Trotsky organised MRC — careful planning vs PG's improvisation"},{text:"Bolsheviks won majority in soviets by September 1917"},{text:"By October PG had almost no supporters willing to defend it"}]},tip:"The question is about PG failure — not Bolshevik success — so keep the focus there. Bolshevik strengths can be mentioned as what the PG faced, not as a separate argument. Structure: inherent weaknesses → policy failures → fatal blow (Kornilov + October)."}
];

const nav = document.getElementById('nav');
const topicsEl = document.getElementById('topics');

topics.forEach((t, i) => {
  const btn = document.createElement('button');
  btn.className = 'nav-btn' + (i === 0 ? ' active' : '');
  btn.textContent = t.num;
  btn.onclick = () => {
    document.querySelectorAll('.nav-btn').forEach(b => b.classList.remove('active'));
    document.querySelectorAll('.topic').forEach(tp => tp.classList.remove('active'));
    btn.classList.add('active');
    document.getElementById('topic-' + i).classList.add('active');
  };
  nav.appendChild(btn);

  const div = document.createElement('div');
  div.className = 'topic' + (i === 0 ? ' active' : '');
  div.id = 'topic-' + i;

  const legendHtml = `<div class="legend">
    <div class="legend-item"><div class="dot dot-lt"></div><span>Long-term / supporting</span></div>
    <div class="legend-item"><div class="dot dot-st"></div><span>Short-term / event</span></div>
    <div class="legend-item"><div class="dot dot-for"></div><span>For argument</span></div>
    <div class="legend-item"><div class="dot dot-against"></div><span>Against / counter</span></div>
  </div>`;

  const col = (c) => c.points.map(p => `<div class="point ${c.color}">${p.text}${p.sub ? `<div class="sub">${p.sub}</div>` : ''}</div>`).join('');

  div.innerHTML = `
    <div class="topic-header">
      <div class="topic-num">${t.num}</div>
      <div class="topic-title">${t.title}</div>
    </div>
    <div class="question-box">${t.question}</div>
    <div class="thesis-box">
      <div class="thesis-label">Suggested thesis</div>
      <div class="thesis-text">${t.thesis}</div>
    </div>
    ${legendHtml}
    <div class="two-col">
      <div class="card"><div class="card-title">${t.columns[0].title}</div>${col(t.columns[0])}</div>
      <div class="card"><div class="card-title">${t.columns[1].title}</div>${col(t.columns[1])}</div>
    </div>
    <div class="one-col">
      <div class="card"><div class="card-title">${t.other.title}</div>${t.other.points.map(p => `<div class="point neu">${p.text}${p.sub ? `<div class="sub">${p.sub}</div>` : ''}</div>`).join('')}</div>
    </div>
    <div class="essay-tip">
      <div class="essay-tip-label">IB essay tip</div>
      <div class="tip-text">${t.tip}</div>
    </div>
  `;
  topicsEl.appendChild(div);
});
</script>
</body>
</html>
